Introduction

There are at least two challenges in this task:

  1. Many NaN slots and distributed differently.
  2. All series are non-stationary because of non-business-days.

Import dataframe and test.

{% raw %} 
assert (n_ts == 500 and max_sz == 5856 and d == 1)
assert check_equal_size(mts['fill0'])
{% endraw %}

1. Agglomerative Hierarchical (Single Linkage)

Ordinary AgglomerativeClustering in sklearn doesn't work if there is NaN in original data set, though it doesn't matter if single linkage is used.

Inspect NaN entries in correlation matrix and set as 0.

{% raw %} 
assert cluster.inspect_nan_corr(data['corr']) == [(463, 485), (485, 463)]
{% endraw %}

Precomputed correlation matrix is used, but result shows big differences in sizes of clusters. So the method cannot be applied.

{% raw %} 
n_clusters = 4
mod = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=n_clusters, affinity='precomputed', linkage='single')
res = mod.fit_predict(data['corr'])
print([list(res).count(i) for i in range(n_clusters)])

[497, 1, 1, 1]
{% endraw %}
